<h4><span class="mw-headline" id="2011">2011</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Linus_Torvalds&amp;action=edit&amp;section=15" title="Edit section: 2011">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h4>
<ul>
<li>Toto, I don't think we're talking white-socks-and-sandals any more.
<ul>
<li>Torvalds (<span class="mw-formatted-date" title="2011-03-01">2011-03-01</span>). <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://torvalds-family.blogspot.com/2011/02/pearls-before-swine.html">pearls before swine</a>. Retrieved on 2011-03-01.</li>
<li>Torvalds contemplating his appearance at an Oscar Party.</li>
</ul>
</li>
</ul>
<ul>
<li>Why don't we write code that just works? Or absent a "just works" set of patches, why don't we revert to code that has years of testing? This kind of "I broke things, so now I will jiggle things randomly until they unbreak" is not acceptable. [...] Don't just make random changes. There really are only two acceptable models of development: "think and analyze" or "years and years of testing on thousands of machines". Those two really do work.
<ul>
<li>Torvalds, Linus (<span class="mw-formatted-date" title="2011-04-13">2011-04-13</span>). <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://thread.gmane.org/gmane.linux.kernel/1126136">Linux 2.6.39-rc3</a>. Retrieved on 2011-04-21.</li>
